76561197995669628,Recommended,261680,29495163,Posted: 25 January,all,Sorokonojka,"Journalis a narrative game about a girl trying to cope with multiple problems in her life. Gameplay is limited to walking and text choices so it is kinda like a 2D walking simulator. The story and drama are very down to earth so it won't appeal to everyone. I usually stay away from a game with no gameplay but good writing and fantastic music won me over.Choice consequences ?Journal is like writing your own story. Your character is innocent unless you decide otherwise. It seems that not everyone likes the main character but I think the point of the game is that you create who she really is.According to some reviews, the choices have no weight to them because they have no impact in a long run. I don't think you can change the ending but you can change side events before that.Sometimes our choices have an impact on us but perhaps can't change certain things in our lives.When I played this game I genuinely cared about the characters. There are some multiple choice answers that will affect your relationships and it will have an impact on this short journey. You will have to play the game about 3 times to collect all extra story cookies.Immersive settings created by MusicHonestly, as soon as I heard the music I knew I would love this game. Without giving away spoilers I will just say that music progressively changes to match the plot. From a sound design point of view, everything was flawless from sound effects to music and voice acting. Not only the music was good but it really complemented the tone of the game.Only about 10% of the game is voice acted from a perspective of the main protagonist. Personally, I prefer games not to be voice acted completely because reading makes me more engaged. Text walls are not too big but If you do not like reading there is no point in buying this game.Enjoyable Art direction and Unique presentation  .Obviously, this game has Kid's drawing vibe to it. When you walk to another screen it flips the page which gave me a weird nostalgia of Sega's Comix Zone ( not related in gameplay obviously ) It is a simple presentation and yet very powerful. Backgrounds have a bit of a surreal take which makes you wonder if the world is real. I guess you could argue that animation could be more fluid but I think it was made clunky on purpose.I am not saying this game has impressive graphics but the art style is used in a way that makes the story more impactful.Score 9/10I enjoyed this game a lot because I could relate to the story but it is not for everyone. If you usually skip text walls and looking for an actual game you probably won't like it. Journal has a good message backed up by good music, creative looks, solid writing and good atmosphere. I would estimate the length around 3 hours if you actually read it but it gives you a reason to play it twice. This game made me cry and I am not afraid to admit it.I felt that a lot of heart went into making Journal, something that only few video games get across."
