76561198058182707,Recommended,261680,22188390,"Posted: 1 April, 2016",all,Leedzie,"Was this game what I expected it to be? No. Is that a bad thing? Maybe not necessarily.I can definitely say that the game struck me on an emotional level; it pretty much nailedhow much it sucks to be in middle school, having friendships go down in flames, a parent abruptly bringing someone new into the picture, and trying to handle the loss of a loved one. It addresses how we can do stupid things in the heat of the moment and not be able to take it back or undo it, and the way that can leech onto your life going forward even if you try to make amends. It also confronts the conflict of selfishness and feeling that you're expected to perform to a certain standard but not being able (or not wanting) to satisfy it.Part of me does wish that there were more distinct consequences for each of my actions, but on some level I kind of appreciate that there aren't.One of the themes of this game is that some things just can't be changed no matter how hard you try, and I caught myself experiencing that on a personal level as I attempted a second playthrough but got similar outcomes.I still think unique consequences would've made the game better, but I don't think it's completely pointless for the game to be without it.Overall, Journal gave me a lot to think about, and even made me cry a few times because it stirred up some incidents from my own past that I too wanted to redo. The controls are a little clunky and it's a bit short, but I'd still give it a go if you're looking for something a little more contemplative. I definitely don't think this game is for everyone, but for those that get invested in a narrative, I think it's worth a play."
76561198006541362,Recommended,261680,16350326,"Posted: 13 June, 2015",all,stranger1982,"Journal is a very simple game that tries to give you some food for thought in regards to depression, social anxiety, loss, friendship and how things change through life.While not completely successful and lacking a certain cohesion it is still a very interesting, albeit somewhat limited, experience.PROS:-really nice art style-good classical soundtrack-touches on several interesting themes-the sudden change of mood made the last chapter very emotionalCONS:-divided between a simple, somewhat ham-fisted, storytelling in the first 4 chapters and some deep, sometimes cryptic, narration during end of the day cutscenes and day 5-pretty short and linear-when using a controller the stick feels very sensitive while choosing conversation options-I couldn't advance the ending scenes using a controller and had to fall back to keyboardhttp://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=460228667Journal seems to be at an empasse on what it is trying to do.The first days are full of day-to-day teen problems and simple musings on the problems the character faces: the conversations are pretty simplistic and somewhat trite in dealing with how everyone feels.The cutscenes at the end of the day start as somewhat cryptic, almost philosophical takes on the feelings that were simplistically addressed during the day: story wise they are explained after the ending but I was left with the feeling that they were designed as a more detailed take on the events of the game.Without spoiling anything, the ending presents a sudden change in mood with a good sense of urgency paired with a good view on loss and the scars life puts on us: it might seem an unoriginal view overall but it was still emotionally powerful.I guess different players'd appreciate the game in different ways...people in their teens'll probably sympatize with the problems and fears the character faces but might feel the cutscenes and ending shift too much into a deep and dark territory. More mature gamers'll probably feel the daily chapers are pretty boring and unoriginal in the way they represent teen problems and will be more interested in trying to understand whether the cutscenes act as metaphors for something deeper: they'll also probably feel very connected with the ending.Despite the problems regarding its identity Journal was a meaningful experience for me, one surely worth its sale price of 2$."
