,Recommended,261680,11142980,"Posted: 8 July, 2014",all,tenniscrazy,"This is a very strange game.  When I first started I thought that it was a game with a decent narrative that was very poorly executed.  You end up being confused and it seems like information that can even seem irrelevant is being shoved at you in the wrong order.  It turns out that this is exactly what Journal is trying to accomplish.I think that if you go into this game with an open mind, try not to play it like an RPG but rather an experiencial narrative, and know that everthing that seems confusing is intentional, It's possible that it will bring you a very personal and emotional experience that only certain Indie games are wont to do.  To the Moon is the other game that comes to mind as a personal and emotional journey, although the two are drastically different in execution; just like To the Moon it is best to play this game in one sitting so as to experience the entity as an undisected whole.I don't guarantee that you will love this game, but take a chance and you just might.  It's definitely not for everybody, but if you enjoy the Indie narrative subgenre(or adventure game without the obsessive clicking as I like to think of it), I would suggest giving it a try."
