,Not Recommended,261680,13142470,"Posted: 29 November, 2014",all,Deisophia,"Journal was fairly disappointing.The attempt to create a plausible yet unreliable narrative character is a rather difficult accomplishment, and Journaljustdidn't manage to get it right. Firstly she constantly tells you what she is doing wrong, there's no guessing the ambiguity of her statements and the final twist to the tale, comes as completely unexpected, there are no hints, or eureka moments of ""Oh this is why they included that!"" In short the game does not encourage reflection, or analysis, it (like so much other modern material from films to books) hamfists you with the truth it wants you to realise rather than allowing an individual interpretation, or playing to multiple meanings through ambiguity. This is no more clearly recognised than when the characters speak in a sequence of randomized letters, that conveys their dialogue without conveying meaning. It's an opt out of revealing subtle clues to the player and feels lazy on the part of the writers rather than illustrating her mental blocks or incapacity to handle her situation.The art style is very childlike, in fact it seemed a bit too childlike considering the adolescent phase the protagonist is portrayed as going through. Yet it has a certain charm, the blurring lines of movement, the overall conceit of playing or moving her through her life as she writes her diary is clever, and the transferral of blocking objects to background desk additions after each daily diary entry is completed are innovative.The support characters are completely unoriginal, from a stay-at-home Mother, who does nothing, to the cliched cast of school characters, it again felt somewhat lazy on the part of the writers, not one character feels truly original or effectively offsets the protagonist, so that her character is actually revealed, not even her selfish interactions with her primary friend Elena as this is contradicted by her opposite interactions with others.As an unreliable narrator we would expect her opinions and interactions with others to be offset by  actual scenarios in the game, but this does not occur at any point. It is also not helped by the stereotypical character designs employed to illustrate these other people, faceless or not. We are shown her perspective and all the events tie in to her persepctive rather than show her to be a delusional liar, which would make far more sense considering the psychological condition of denial they attempt to portray her as being in.The bridging story of the Carnival, intrigued me at first, although I cringed through the monotone of the male voice-over narrator for these parts. I wondered at first at the symbolic significance that they were attempting to use with the portrayal of the carnival, and although it does serve this in a minor capacity the ultimate integration of the carnival into the main storyline, simply destroyed any symbolic function it could have served and denigrated it into a literal truth.The gameplay itself is fairly smooth and reliable, and area transitions occur quickly without any long delays or interruptions allowing the story to continue at a fairly rapid pace. The only issue is that once the story is completed there isn't much replay value, as interactions don't seem to affect the outcome at all, in fact the only reason to replay would be to try achieve a 100% completion of achievements. In short there is not much longevity to the title.Overall I don't recommend Journal, it's not as poor as I make it out above, but neither is it actually good. In short it is fairly average title, without replayability that means you're probably better off spending your money on another title or buying this only when it's on sale."
76561198078365202,Not Recommended,261680,13177810,"Posted: 1 December, 2014",all,IceAriE,"Very hard decision, But 51% of me would not recommend this game.I don’t want to spoil the game, but for me, at the start, it's normal to get confused in games or stories, ""it'll make sense later on, don't worry!""(What I said to myself). But in the middle to the near end, I was still confused about the divorce, in fact, it was only until the middle-end I found out it was a divorce(I was that confused) and had to infer to figure out that the protagonist’s mum cheated on her father with John(I think that was his name, but he was a farmer guy).But maybe that’s just the 12ive perspective. Speaking about that, when you had to make the decisions, I had to search up some of the words so i knew i was making the right decisions: /.I had especially been confused with the about the carnival cut scenes. At first, I thought they were like her dreams(since the cut scenes would start when she came home and a new day would start after them) and then I thought of them having a meaning into what you would choose, like you had to learn a lessons from the cut scenes to be successful in the game. I turns out *Minor SPOILER* that it wasn’t something random, but it was to intensify the happy place the carnival was before the closing. But what i hated the most about this game, was the fact that it was intentionally un-organised. The creator told you a major event at the very end of the game, to show you how cowardly she/he was, and how she didn’t want to face it, and ran away from her past. This part made me think and say to myself ""This game was telling everyone how depressed she was, as she lived a life of a girl who chose so many wrong mistakes in her early life and causing various problems, but most importantly, showing everyone how she ran away from everything. But at least the moral was to not end up like her, so selfish and heartless.""On the bright side, this game had an art style that I wish more games were like, which lead me to why i bought the game. I also liked the idea of the creator making us the troublesome protagonist, because was it not only unique, but interesting in a way that it would make us feel irritated and regrettable in the decisions that we were forced to play with, so we could see the creator view in wishing we would regret the actions done.Overall, I think this game would be a nice game for people who want to play a different game, a game where you will lose, possibly feel heart-stuck(if your a softie like me) and have most of the storyline make sense at the very, bitter, end. By this game in like the Christmas/summer sales if you are up for the experience."
