,Not Recommended,261680,14106197,"Posted: 21 January, 2015",all,Tsundere Supp,"I want to recommend this game, I really do, but the gameplay detracts from the story too much to actually make me want to tell someone to sit down and play it through. First off I bought this game for maybe $2 on a steam sale. It was something I'd seen a few times and passed up because it didn't look like my type of visual novel. But it was; it was just executed poorly. First off your decisions barely matter. Only if you want the losing a friend achievement does it matter what you choose along the way (and I just so happened to toss myself down that road in my first playthrough) and even then losing a friend doesn't change the outcome. The ending is pretty much disjointed from every event along the way. Sure the ending explains her rotten mood, but the ending is more of a 'this is why I'm acting so sour' kind of backstory than it is 'these are the consequences of my actions' which is what you would expect a series of choices to lead you to. I could live with that (even though the completionist in me wants to truck through and read all the dialogue for every option) if it was the only downside of the game.What really gets me though is not the lack of options in the game. It's the feel of the world itself. The MCs voice is very nice and I can appreciate the music of the game, but switching from page to page is a bit of a headache. The pages seem to shift in a very awkward manner looking like it's flickering between the two pages before you finally settle on the second screen and half of the time the MC jumps when she gets there. If she was at the edge of the screen when it was flickering all of a sudden she's in a middle as if the game was trying to disorient you. Day 3 was the worst of it due to a bug that can jump you into the journal pages of Day 5 (except you can't interact with anyone and then you get kicked out of it and think you were doing something wrong and kicked yourself out of Day 3's plot). Overall I felt like I was tussling with the journal pages more than working with it to immerse myself in a story line.On top of the bad scene transitioning is the disjointed day transitioning. Each day ends with a screen shift into what looks like a puppet show telling you a 'story' that is supposed to connect with the main story line. On most days it feels as though the author of the game forgot where we was going with the story and abruptly cut it short before the final conclusion. At first it seems like an isolated event, but once you get to the end of the game you realize that the end of day stories are like most things, cut off without a proper end. There is never an explanation of the package, or her grandmother's behavior, characters like Heather are briefly mentioned and treated as if they'd been there since day one but are really never there at all. The whole incident with John is never flat out explained either-- it's the only piece of the plot that it seems as if the author purposely avoided saying and yet it is the only piece that you can logically draw a conclusion to because everybody knows what really happened.On top of that the game forces achievement hunters to go back through day one all over again looking for a secret ending that adds no depth to the story at all. As if the gameplay wasn't frustrating enough the first time they developers make us take a motion sickening gander across day one all over again to try and 'cheer us up' with a whole bunch of nothing.If you get it on sale, the story (despite it's holes) is cute and will leave you feeling a little heavy, and the achievements are easy to get if that's all you're looking for, but the interface and scene changes just aren't worth the story in my opinion."
