,Recommended,261680,19898929,"Posted: 23 December, 2015",all,Lime11,"I'm not really sure what to say about this game. I feel like I should probably wait a day or two before writing this review, but if I do that, the emotional charge that's in me will go away.First of, this isn't a puzzle game. Or even a game really. It's an interactive story with dialouge choices along the way. Some of these choices (or maybe even most of them) don't really hold much consequence and most of the results are quite predictable. This isn't a problem however. It's the moment that you make the choice that really matters. You sit there weighing the options next to eachother, knowing fully well what will happen when you choose either one. Just like in real life.Nearly all of the choices we make in life feel predictable to ourselves. We understand that when we lie, either someone will discover the truth or we will be wondering whether or not someone will discover the truth for the rest of our lives. Once we actually follow through with the lie howerver, we constantly think about what would of happened if we told the truth.Which, in my humble opinion, is this game's greatest strength. It makes all of the choices feel like choices that we one day could make ourselves, and shows us how people may or may not react to those choices. I found it to be extremely compelling.The story it's self is quite uninteresting, particularly the first two days. It comes across as rather uninspired and pointless and I was rather underwhelmed. Keep in mind while trudging through it, that it is actually pretty important and you should pay attention. Although I found it rather dull, it's quite complex and the characters come across as quite relatable and human. You'll know someone just like nearly everyone you meet in this game.Something also needs to be said about the art style and music. Although it's nothing that would drop a jaw, it suits the mood and story very well. The world looks and feels tense, which makes the later parts of the plot seem much more interesting. The whole game you're wondering why everything is so depressing and dim until you finally reach the ending where everything falls nicely into place, bringing forth understanding for certain design choices.This game isn't for everyone. Not even for most. There are no puzzles or gameplay, only walking around and making choices. But the choices themselves are what made this game worth it for me. I sat in this chair at the end thinking about why I do what I do and considering the effect these choices are having on other people. If you're looking for an experience similar to the one I just described, then I heartely recommend this game to you."
