76561198064527485,Recommended,261680,9689944,"Posted: 31 March, 2014",all,wolfgirl3,"Teenage Girl Problems: The Video GameFirst of all, I do NOT recommend this game if you're having a hard time in your life, or if you are looking for a game with lots of explosions and difficult puzzles.That having been said, I DO recommend this game to people who have a fondness for interactive storytelling. Journal deals with growing up and making mistakes, as well as suffering the consequences. It's gameplay is very simple and easy to figure out, but dealing with EVERYONE'S issues makes it a little emotionally draining. Some people you can make ammends with(such as Mr. Collinsworth), but with others(like Elena the Abominable Super♥♥♥♥♥) it seems like no matter what you do, they just won't accept your apologies.It's a lot like real life, and helping your character through her problems can be both rewarding and frustrating."
,Recommended,261680,9924163,"Posted: 24 April, 2014",all,Sachi,"First off, don't buy this game if you're looking for a fast-paced adventure experience, because you will not find that here. Instead, you'll find a visual novel with a boatload of symbolism and some interesting concepts. The story is slow-paced, but it's deep if you can read between the lines, and even more so when you reach the end of the game.I love Journal. There's a LOT I can say about it, but not so much without spoilers. So I'll talk about the aspects I liked about the game briefly and generally.You make decisions on the protagonist's attitude towards other characters in the game. Now, that on it's own might now seem like much. There are tons of games that let you do that. These decisions don't even have much affect on the game in the long run. It's a linear storyline. Still, that was just something I liked about it.Some decisions do affect the game, and these are probably the biggest reason I love Journal. In one part of the game, the protagonist faces a challenge that she can choose to accept assistance in facing. I think that's a lot deeper than it may seem. Really, it says a lot about human nature. We don't like to reach out for help sometimes, but in reality, it would make the situation so much better. Then, immediately following that choice, you get to choose whether or not to let your mother know that you had trouble completing the task, and whether or not you seeked help for it. That's another interesting tidbit on our nature. Even if we choose to accept help on things, often times, we don't want it to be known that we did so. I suppose we just want to make ourselves look better by making it seem as if we've done everything on our own.The thing that impacted me the most in this game was the choice of whether or not to fess up to something you have done. I played through this part twice, and I know both of the ways the story could go from there. Of course, I'm not going to say it for respect for those who do not appreciate spoilers, but I thought it was a very deep decision, and it really impacted me and really made me love Journal even more.I also love the soundtrack to Journal. I just find it to be beautiful. The art style is attractive as well, featuring a hand-drawn feel to the graphics. It suits the game well as it is supposed to be inside of a Journal.By now, if you've read this far, you can see pretty clearly that I'm a huge fan of symbolism. So another thing that I really appreciated in the game was the shadow puppet shows after each chapter. At first, I was confused, and I didn't like the shadow puppet shows. I thought they were fillers with no meaning and no input to the developing story. They just seemed meaningless and unnecessary. However, as I progressed through the story and thought deeply about what each character may have been thinking or feeling based on their actions in the game, I realized that the shadow puppet shows were symbolically linked to the main story. In fact, if you really think about the stories presented, they're surprisingly easy to link the symbolism. I realized that, really, the shadow puppet shows are a brilliant addition to the experience.If you are patient enough to get through the slow story, you will not be disappointed."
,Recommended,261680,13529199,"Posted: 22 December, 2014",all,KaleeshWarrior,"This game is a masterpiece and I cannot recommend it enough. I was mostly drawn to this game due to the artistic style, and that certainly didn't disappoint. Journal has an aesthetic that I've never really seen anywhere else, and it makes good use of it throughout.While I came for the aesthetic, I stayed for Journal's narrative and writing. It's a game where the character you play as is an actual character: she does things you don't want her to do, she says things you don't want her to say, and she keeps secrets from you. Constantly. It also is a game about choice, but also not. It's really just a game about life and living and how consequences will always be there, no matter how hard you try to outrun them or erase them.Journal is, at its essence, about the human experience of storytelling. It's about the stories we tell ourselves about ourselves to try and make sense of ourselves, our worlds, and our lives."
